{"title_page": "Addison Rae", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|American social media personality}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Addison Rae\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Addison Rae Easterling\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|2000|10|6}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lafayette, Louisiana]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[Internet celebrity|Social media personality]]|Dancer}}\n| years_active       = 2019\u2013present\n| known_for          = [[TikTok]]\n| relatives          = Alex Geelmuyden, Denise Evju\n}}\n\n'''Addison Rae Easterling''' (born October 6, 2000), colloquially known as '''Addison Rae''', is an [[United States|American]] [[Internet celebrity|social media personality]] and dancer. As of April 2020, she has accumulated 1.6 billion likes and 34.1 million followers on the social video sharing app [[TikTok]], being the [[List of most-followed TikTok accounts|6th most-followed individual on the platform]]. Addison Rae also is a member of the Hype House, and is one of the fastest-growing TikTok users. Her family are incredibly active on social media, and all together have reached above 70M followers! Along with Addison\u2019s family, her lifelong friend, Margaret (she can be found on TikTok as @TiktokerMargaret) is incredibly supportive with Addison\u2018s career choice.\n\n==Biography==\nAddison Rae Easterling was born on October 6, 2000, in [[Lafayette, Louisiana]], to Monty Lopez and Sheri Easterling<ref name=\"seven\">{{cite web |url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/a31823306/who-is-addison-rae-easterling/ |title=Everything You Need to Know About TikTok Star Addison Rae |last=Kim |first=Yerin |date=March 20, 2020 |website=[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}} </ref>. She also has two brothers named Enzo and Lucas.<ref name=\"seven\" /> She grew up in [[Lafayette, Louisiana]]. She attended [[Louisiana State University]], in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]. Before moving to Los Angeles to pursue TikTok, the dancer attended [[Calvary Baptist Academy (Shreveport, Louisiana)|Calvary Baptist Academy]] in [[Shreveport, Louisiana]].<ref name=\"sbmag\">{{cite web |url=https://sbmag.net/sb-art-junior-addison-easterling-calvary-baptist-academy/ |title=SB Art Junior: Addison Easterling, Calvary Baptist Academy |date=March 2019 |website=SB Mag |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe joined the TikTok platform in July of 2019.<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/katetalbot/2020/04/07/meet-addison-rae-one-of-tiktoks-biggest-stars/#4f515fa671ed |title=Meet Addison Rae, One Of TikTok\u2019s Biggest Stars |last=Talbot |first=Kate |date=April 7, 2020 |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> She has been part of the TikTok collaborative group [[The Hype House]] along with 18 others, including [[Charli D'Amelio]] and Dixie D'Amelio.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/03/style/hype-house-los-angeles-tik-tok.html |title=Hype House and the Los Angeles TikTok Mansion Gold Rush |last=Lorenz |first=Taylor |date=January 3, 2020 |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Easterling signed with talent agency [[Endeavor (company)|WME]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tiktoker-addison-rae-signs-wme-1271521 |title=TikToker Addison Rae Signs With WME (Exclusive) |last=Jarvey |first=Natalie |date=January 21, 2020 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{TikTok}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n* {{IMDb name}} \n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rae, Addison}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dancers]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Female TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lafayette, Louisiana]]\n__INDEX__\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|American social media personality}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Addison Rae\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Addison Rae Easterling\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|2000|10|6}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lafayette, Louisiana]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[Internet celebrity|Social media personality]]|Dancer}}\n| years_active       = 2019\u2013present\n| known_for          = [[TikTok]]\n| relatives          = Alex Geelmuyden, Denise Evju\n}}\n\n'''Addison Rae Easterling''' (born October 6, 2000), colloquially known as '''Addison Rae''', is an [[United States|American]] [[Internet celebrity|social media personality]] and dancer. As of April 2020, she has accumulated 1.6 billion likes and 34.1 million followers on the social video sharing app [[TikTok]], being the [[List of most-followed TikTok accounts|6th most-followed individual on the platform]].\n\n==Biography==\nAddison Rae Easterling was born on October 6, 2000, in [[Lafayette, Louisiana]], to Monty Lopez and Sheri Easterling<ref name=\"seven\">{{cite web |url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/a31823306/who-is-addison-rae-easterling/ |title=Everything You Need to Know About TikTok Star Addison Rae |last=Kim |first=Yerin |date=March 20, 2020 |website=[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}} </ref>. She also has two brothers named Enzo and Lucas.<ref name=\"seven\" /> She grew up in [[Lafayette, Louisiana]]. She attended [[Louisiana State University]], in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]. Before moving to Los Angeles to pursue TikTok, the dancer attended [[Calvary Baptist Academy (Shreveport, Louisiana)|Calvary Baptist Academy]] in [[Shreveport, Louisiana]].<ref name=\"sbmag\">{{cite web |url=https://sbmag.net/sb-art-junior-addison-easterling-calvary-baptist-academy/ |title=SB Art Junior: Addison Easterling, Calvary Baptist Academy |date=March 2019 |website=SB Mag |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe joined the TikTok platform in July of 2019.<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/katetalbot/2020/04/07/meet-addison-rae-one-of-tiktoks-biggest-stars/#4f515fa671ed |title=Meet Addison Rae, One Of TikTok\u2019s Biggest Stars |last=Talbot |first=Kate |date=April 7, 2020 |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> She has been part of the TikTok collaborative group [[The Hype House]] along with 18 others, including [[Charli D'Amelio]] and Dixie D'Amelio.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/03/style/hype-house-los-angeles-tik-tok.html |title=Hype House and the Los Angeles TikTok Mansion Gold Rush |last=Lorenz |first=Taylor |date=January 3, 2020 |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Easterling signed with talent agency [[Endeavor (company)|WME]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tiktoker-addison-rae-signs-wme-1271521 |title=TikToker Addison Rae Signs With WME (Exclusive) |last=Jarvey |first=Natalie |date=January 21, 2020 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{TikTok}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n* {{IMDb name}} \n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rae, Addison}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dancers]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Female TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lafayette, Louisiana]]\n__INDEX__\n", "name_user": "Sarahmcdonaldsss", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added lots of errors and vital info that were not added to the page z)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addison_Rae"}
{"title_page": "Bob Schaefer", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Bob Schaefer\n|image=Bob Schaefer (manager) - Memphis Chicks - 1987.jpg\n|caption=Schaefer in 1987\n|team=\n|number=\n|position=[[Coach (baseball)|Coach]]/[[Manager (baseball)|Interim manager]]\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1944|5|22}}\n|birth_place=[[Putnam, Connecticut]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|statleague=MLB\n|stat1label=Games managed\n|stat1value=18\n|stat2label=[[Manager (baseball)|Managerial record]]\n|stat2value=6\u201312\n|stat3label=[[Winning percentage]]\n|stat3value=.333\n|teams=\n'''As manager'''\n*[[Kansas City Royals]] ({{mlby|1991}}; {{mlby|2005}})\n'''As coach'''\n*[[Kansas City Royals]] ({{mlby|1988}}\u2013{{mlby|1991}}; {{mlby|2002}}\u2013{{mlby|2005}})\n*[[Oakland Athletics]] ({{mlby|2007}})\n*[[Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|2008}}\u2013{{mlby|2010}})\n}}\n'''Robert Walden Schaefer''' (born May 22, 1944, in [[Putnam, Connecticut]]) is a former [[interim manager]], [[coach (baseball)|bench coach]] and [[farm system]] official in American [[Major League Baseball]]. He is currently the special assistant to the [[general manager (baseball)|general manager]] with the [[Washington Nationals]].\n\n== Playing career ==\nSchaefer attended the [[University of Connecticut]], graduating in 1966. He was a member of the UConn [[College World Series]] team in 1965, when he was the team captain and the [[NCAA]] [[home run]] champion. \n\nIn 1965, Schaefer played [[collegiate summer baseball]] for the [[Bourne Braves|Sagamore Clouters]] of the [[Cape Cod Baseball League]] (CCBL), leading Sagamore to the league title under field manager [[Lou Lamoriello]]. He returned to manage the CCBL's [[Bourne Braves|Bourne Canalmen]] in 1971 and 1972, and [[Hyannis Harbor Hawks|Hyannis Mets]] in 1978 and 1979, winning league titles in both years with Hyannis. Schaefer was inducted into the CCBL hall of fame in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://capecodbaseball.org/news/hofnews/?article_id=215 |title=CCBL Hall of Fame Announced |publisher=capecodbaseball.org |date= |accessdate=September 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was drafted as a [[shortstop]] by the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] in 1966, but never reached the major leagues in three seasons with the organization. He progressed as far as [[Modesto, California|Modesto]] in the High A [[California League]]. Schaefer batted left-handed and threw right-handed.\n\nIn 2005, Schaefer received the Distinguished Alumni Award from UConn, primarily for his achievements on that College World Series team.\n\nHE IS ALSO A SUPER GRUMPY OLD FART AND A BAND TEACHER\n\n==Coaching and managing career==\nTwice, Schaefer has served as the interim pilot of the [[Kansas City Royals]]. In 1991, he was interim manager during the period between managers [[John Wathan]] and [[Hal McRae]]. In 2005, he succeeded [[Tony Pe\u00f1a]] on May 11 and served through May 30. On May 31, 2005, [[Buddy Bell]] took the reins as permanent manager and Schaefer returned to the bench coach position. Schaefer's position with the Royals was terminated at the end of the 2005 season, the worst in Royals history.\n\nHe began his managerial career in the [[Minor League Baseball|minor leagues]], where he won numerous awards. He was twice named Manager of the Year (in 1980 and 1981) at Class A [[Greensboro Grasshoppers|Greensboro]], then a part of the [[New York Yankees]] organization. He also managed the [[New York Mets]]' Class AAA team in [[Norfolk Tides|Tidewater]] to an [[International League]] championship in 1985.\n\nHe first joined the Royals organization in 1987, managing the Class AA [[Memphis Chicks]]. His first major-league job was as the Royals' [[Coach (baseball)|first base coach]] from 1988 to 1990, then he was the Royals' bench coach in 1991. He worked as a special assignment scout with the Royals in 1992.\n\nSchaefer then moved on to the [[Boston Red Sox]] organization, serving as a special assignment scout and later the director of player development from 1994 to the midseason of 1998. During that time, he hired [[Bob Geren]] as a manager in the Boston farm system; a decade later, when Geren was named the 2007 manager of the [[Oakland Athletics]], he brought Schaefer to Oakland as bench coach on his staff.\n\nAlthough Schaefer received positive notices for his work as the Red Sox' player development chief, he clashed with [[general manager]] [[Dan Duquette]] and was fired during the summer of 1998; several minor league managers and coaches, including Geren, departed the organization with Schaefer, who spent the next three years as a special assistant to the general manager of the [[Baltimore Orioles]] before returning to the Royals in 2001 as a bench coach and infielders coach.\n\nAfter his 2005 departure from Kansas City, he spent 2006 as a special assignment [[scout (sport)|scout]] with the [[Atlanta Braves]].  He was bench coach for the [[Oakland Athletics]] in 2007, and was named to the same role for the Dodgers and its new manager, [[Joe Torre]], for the 2008 season, a role he held through 2010. After Torre's retirement, Schaefer announced he would not return on the staff of incoming manager [[Don Mattingly]], saying that he thought Mattingly should pick a younger coach who could continue for a number of years.<ref>[http://losangeles.dodgers.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101003&content_id=15382160&notebook_id=15402778&vkey=notebook_la&c_id=la Dodgers' coaching staff uncertain for 2011]</ref>\n\nHis career record as an MLB manager is 6\u201312 (.333), including his 5\u201312 mark during his 2005 tenure.\n\n==Managerial records==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! colspan=\"4\"|Regular Season !! colspan=\"4\"|Post Season\n|-\n! Won !! Lost !! Win % !! Finish !! Won !! Lost !! Win % !! Result\n|-\n![[1991 Kansas City Royals season|KC]]||1991\n||1 ||0 ||1.000 ||'''6th in [[AL West]]''' || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n![[2005 Kansas City Royals season|KC]]||2005\n||5 ||12 ||.294 ||'''5th in [[AL Central]]''' || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n*John Montague, ed., ''New York Mets 1985 Organization Book''. St. Petersburg, Florida: Baseball Library, 1985.\n \n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=[[List of Los Angeles Dodgers coaches|Los Angeles Dodgers Bench Coach]] | before=[[Dave Jauss]] | years=2008\u20132010 | after=[[Trey Hillman]]}}  \n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Kansas City Royals managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schaefer, Bob}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Braves scouts]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles executives]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles scouts]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox executives]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox scouts]]\n[[Category:Bourne Braves players]]\n[[Category:Cape Cod Baseball League coaches]]\n[[Category:Cape Cod Baseball League hall of fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Cedar Rapids Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals coaches]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals managers]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals scouts]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball bench coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball farm directors]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball first base coaches]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball managers]]\n[[Category:Modesto Reds players]]\n[[Category:Norfolk Tides managers]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics coaches]]\n[[Category:People from Putnam, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Rock Hill Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Washington Nationals scouts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Bob Schaefer\n|image=Bob Schaefer (manager) - Memphis Chicks - 1987.jpg\n|caption=Schaefer in 1987\n|team=\n|number=\n|position=[[Coach (baseball)|Coach]]/[[Manager (baseball)|Interim manager]]\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1944|5|22}}\n|birth_place=[[Putnam, Connecticut]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|statleague=MLB\n|stat1label=Games managed\n|stat1value=18\n|stat2label=[[Manager (baseball)|Managerial record]]\n|stat2value=6\u201312\n|stat3label=[[Winning percentage]]\n|stat3value=.333\n|teams=\n'''As manager'''\n*[[Kansas City Royals]] ({{mlby|1991}}; {{mlby|2005}})\n'''As coach'''\n*[[Kansas City Royals]] ({{mlby|1988}}\u2013{{mlby|1991}}; {{mlby|2002}}\u2013{{mlby|2005}})\n*[[Oakland Athletics]] ({{mlby|2007}})\n*[[Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|2008}}\u2013{{mlby|2010}})\n}}\n'''Robert Walden Schaefer''' (born May 22, 1944, in [[Putnam, Connecticut]]) is a former [[interim manager]], [[coach (baseball)|bench coach]] and [[farm system]] official in American [[Major League Baseball]]. He is currently the special assistant to the [[general manager (baseball)|general manager]] with the [[Washington Nationals]].\n\n== Playing career ==\nSchaefer attended the [[University of Connecticut]], graduating in 1966. He was a member of the UConn [[College World Series]] team in 1965, when he was the team captain and the [[NCAA]] [[home run]] champion. \n\nIn 1965, Schaefer played [[collegiate summer baseball]] for the [[Bourne Braves|Sagamore Clouters]] of the [[Cape Cod Baseball League]] (CCBL), leading Sagamore to the league title under field manager [[Lou Lamoriello]]. He returned to manage the CCBL's [[Bourne Braves|Bourne Canalmen]] in 1971 and 1972, and [[Hyannis Harbor Hawks|Hyannis Mets]] in 1978 and 1979, winning league titles in both years with Hyannis. Schaefer was inducted into the CCBL hall of fame in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://capecodbaseball.org/news/hofnews/?article_id=215 |title=CCBL Hall of Fame Announced |publisher=capecodbaseball.org |date= |accessdate=September 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was drafted as a [[shortstop]] by the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] in 1966, but never reached the major leagues in three seasons with the organization. He progressed as far as [[Modesto, California|Modesto]] in the High A [[California League]]. Schaefer batted left-handed and threw right-handed.\n\nIn 2005, Schaefer received the Distinguished Alumni Award from UConn, primarily for his achievements on that College World Series team.\n\n==Coaching and managing career==\nTwice, Schaefer has served as the interim pilot of the [[Kansas City Royals]]. In 1991, he was interim manager during the period between managers [[John Wathan]] and [[Hal McRae]]. In 2005, he succeeded [[Tony Pe\u00f1a]] on May 11 and served through May 30. On May 31, 2005, [[Buddy Bell]] took the reins as permanent manager and Schaefer returned to the bench coach position. Schaefer's position with the Royals was terminated at the end of the 2005 season, the worst in Royals history.\n\nHe began his managerial career in the [[Minor League Baseball|minor leagues]], where he won numerous awards. He was twice named Manager of the Year (in 1980 and 1981) at Class A [[Greensboro Grasshoppers|Greensboro]], then a part of the [[New York Yankees]] organization. He also managed the [[New York Mets]]' Class AAA team in [[Norfolk Tides|Tidewater]] to an [[International League]] championship in 1985.\n\nHe first joined the Royals organization in 1987, managing the Class AA [[Memphis Chicks]]. His first major-league job was as the Royals' [[Coach (baseball)|first base coach]] from 1988 to 1990, then he was the Royals' bench coach in 1991. He worked as a special assignment scout with the Royals in 1992.\n\nSchaefer then moved on to the [[Boston Red Sox]] organization, serving as a special assignment scout and later the director of player development from 1994 to the midseason of 1998. During that time, he hired [[Bob Geren]] as a manager in the Boston farm system; a decade later, when Geren was named the 2007 manager of the [[Oakland Athletics]], he brought Schaefer to Oakland as bench coach on his staff.\n\nAlthough Schaefer received positive notices for his work as the Red Sox' player development chief, he clashed with [[general manager]] [[Dan Duquette]] and was fired during the summer of 1998; several minor league managers and coaches, including Geren, departed the organization with Schaefer, who spent the next three years as a special assistant to the general manager of the [[Baltimore Orioles]] before returning to the Royals in 2001 as a bench coach and infielders coach.\n\nAfter his 2005 departure from Kansas City, he spent 2006 as a special assignment [[scout (sport)|scout]] with the [[Atlanta Braves]].  He was bench coach for the [[Oakland Athletics]] in 2007, and was named to the same role for the Dodgers and its new manager, [[Joe Torre]], for the 2008 season, a role he held through 2010. After Torre's retirement, Schaefer announced he would not return on the staff of incoming manager [[Don Mattingly]], saying that he thought Mattingly should pick a younger coach who could continue for a number of years.<ref>[http://losangeles.dodgers.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101003&content_id=15382160&notebook_id=15402778&vkey=notebook_la&c_id=la Dodgers' coaching staff uncertain for 2011]</ref>\n\nHis career record as an MLB manager is 6\u201312 (.333), including his 5\u201312 mark during his 2005 tenure.\n\n==Managerial records==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! colspan=\"4\"|Regular Season !! colspan=\"4\"|Post Season\n|-\n! Won !! Lost !! Win % !! Finish !! Won !! Lost !! Win % !! Result\n|-\n![[1991 Kansas City Royals season|KC]]||1991\n||1 ||0 ||1.000 ||'''6th in [[AL West]]''' || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n![[2005 Kansas City Royals season|KC]]||2005\n||5 ||12 ||.294 ||'''5th in [[AL Central]]''' || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n*John Montague