rty shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1920|1920]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|30.3% ''344''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''69.1%''' ''784''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.5% ''6''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1916|1916]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|27.2% ''184''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''72.2%''' ''489''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.6% ''4''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1912|1912]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|15.2% ''86''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''71.6%''' ''405''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|13.3% ''75''\n|}\n\nJuly 1, 2019 to June 30, 2020:\n\nGovernment\n* Mayor: Neal Osborne \n* Vice Mayor: Bill Hartley \n* Council Member: Kevin Wingard\n* Council Member: Kevin Mumpower\n* Council Member: Anthony Farnum\n* Interim City Manager: Randall C. Eads\n* Assistant City Manager:\n\n===Past mayors===\n[[File:Bristol city hall, Virginia.jpg|thumb|right|250px|City Hall]]\n* Jerry Wolfe, 1992-1997\n* Farham Jarrard, 1997-2000\n* Jerry Wolfe, 2000-2001\n* Douglas R. Weberling, 2001-2003\n* Jerry Wolfe, 2003-2004\n* Paul W. Hurley, 2004-2005\n* Douglas R. Weberling, 2005-2006\n* C. Farnham Jarrard, 2006-2007\n* James Rector, 2007-2010\n* Don Ashley, 2010-2011\n* Ed Harlow, 2011-2012\n* Jim Steele, 2012-2013\n* Guy Odum, 2013-2014\n* Catherine Brillhart, 2014-2015 (first female mayor)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tricities.com/news/article_4a820b62-012f-11e4-a832-0017a43b2370.html|title=Brillhart named Bristol, Virginia mayor|work=HeraldCourier.com|accessdate=5 December 2015}}</ref>\n* Archie Hubbard, III, 2015-2016\n* Bill Hartley, 2016-2017\n* Kevin Mumpower, 2017-2019\n\n===Police===\n{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n|agencyname = Bristol Police Department\n|abbreviation = BPD\n|country = United States\n|divtype = State\n|divname = Virginia\n|subdivtype = City\n|subdivname = Bristol\n|police  = Yes\n|local  = Yes\n|formedyear     =\n|sworn  = 53\n|unsworn = 21\n|chief1name = John S. Austin\n|chief1position = Chief\n|website = [website]\n}}\n\nBristol is served by two law enforcement agencies: the city police and the city sheriff's department.  Supporting the department is the city's E-911 Central Dispatch Emergency Communication Center which provides call taking and dispatch service for police, fire and EMS needs.\n\n== Technology ==\nDespite its relatively small size, Bristol, Virginia, boasts one of the more advanced [[broadband]] networks in the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Broadband at the Speed of Light|url=https://ilsr.org/broadband-speed-light/|publisher=Institute for Local Self-Reliance|accessdate=4 December 2015|date=9 April 2012}}</ref> BVU Authority (formerly Bristol Virginia Utilities or BVU)<ref>{{cite web |title=Virginia SCC - Division of Public Utility Registration |url=https://www.scc.virginia.gov/pur/phone/tariff.aspx |website=SCC of Virginia |accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> started planning a [[fiber optic]] deployment in the city in the late 1990s. By 2001, BVU had been granted approval by the city council for a full deployment of a [[Fiber to the premises]] (FTTP or FTTU, fiber to the user) project. This project was to offer competition to local incumbents and provide broadband Internet, cable TV, and telephone service to the residents of Bristol. This deployment was one of the first of its kind in the United States and was widely watched by the telecommunications industry. A system known as [[Passive optical network]] (PON) was successfully deployed to over 6,000 customers in a matter of two years.\n\nIn 2003, in the relatively isolated city of Bristol, Virginia, BVU, created a nonprofit division called \"Optinet\", a municipal broadband Internet service that covers Bristol as well as the Southwest portion of the state of Virginia. Serving around 12,500 customers,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web\n |url          = http://www.bvu-optinet.com/index.php/about-us/corporate-history\n |title        = Bristol Virginia utilities: about us\n |website      = Bvu-optinet.com\n |access-date  = 2017-05-24\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170606215655/http://bvu-optinet.com/index.php/about-us/corporate-history\n |archive-date = 2017-06-06\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> BVU is recognized as the \"first municipal utility in the United States to deploy an all-fiber network offering the triple play of video, voice and data services\".<ref name=\":0\" /> On October 29, 2009, BVU received US$3.5 million in grant funding from the Virginia Tobacco Indemnification and Community Revitalization Commission.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.lightwaveonline.com/fttx/news/Bristol-Virginia-Utilities-receives-35-million-for-broadband-construction-68665447.html\n| title = Bristol Virginia Utilities receives $3.5 million for broadband construction\n| website = www.lightwaveonline.com\n| access-date = 2016-02-29\n}}</ref> With these funds BVU will build \"an additional 49 miles of its OptiNet fiber-optic backbone from Abingdon up I-81 to Virginia Route 16 from Marion into Grayson County\".<ref name=\":1\" /> This will also allow for BVU to make a second connection with Mid Atlantic Broadband, increasing communication between different businesses in Northern Virginia. The Virginia Tobacco Community funded this project because it provided their business with more connections in crucial areas of the southwest and southern part of Virginia.\n\nThe U.S. Department of Commerce also funded BVU. On July 3, 2010, it was reported that they gave US$22.7 million in stimulus funds to Southwest Virginia to create a \"388-mile optic backbone through an eight-county region\". This project will service over 120 institutions, such as schools, hospitals, government buildings, and many more besides.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web\n| url = http://bdtonline.com/local/x1671038013/Stimulus-funding-to-stretch-broadband-through-8-Va-counties\n| title = Stimulus funding to stretch broadband through 8 Va. counties\n| last = Telegraph\n| first = CHARLES OWENSBluefield Daily\n| website = Bluefield Daily Telegraph\n| access-date = 2016-02-29\n}}</ref> This new municipals broadband service will also be within a two-mile distance of over 500 different businesses.<ref name=\":2\" /> This project also created 295 new jobs.<ref name=\":2\" /> BVU Optinet continues operate a strong municipal broadband Internet service for Bristol and many other counties in Virginia.\n\nBristol's twin city in Tennessee has deployed an FTTP system similar to its neighbor across the state line.\n\nOn August 2, 2018, BVU Authority completed a sale of the OptiNet FTTP network to a private company, Sunset Digital of [[Duffield, Virginia]] for $50 M.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McGee |first1=David |title=Sunset, BVU OptiNet deal finalized |url=https://www.heraldcourier.com/news/sunset-bvu-optinet-deal-finalized/article_8b746332-2ee1-5565-b52f-8678020c9277.html |accessdate=5 August 2018 |agency=Bristol Herald Courier |publisher=Bristol Herald Courier}}</ref> The sale began in late 2015 and was publicly announced in early 2016. Along with the sale of OptiNet, BVU's joint network with Cumberland Plateau Co. was sold to Sunset Digital. In addition to the network assets, Sunset agreed to hire approximately 75 BVU employees from BVU.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Irby |first1=Zach |title=BVU OptiNet, Sunset deal moving forward |url=https://www.heraldcourier.com/news/bvu-optinet-sunset-deal-moving-forward/article_45fba0d1-f3c6-5d92-9422-e2ee2db7a70e.html |accessdate=5 August 2018 |agency=BRISTOL HERALD COURIER |publisher=BRISTOL HERALD COURIER}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n===Air transport===\nThe [[Tri-Cities Regional Airport]], with approximately 195,000 annual passengers, is 19 miles to the southwest of Bristol.<ref>U.S. Department of Transportation, Bureau of Transportation Statistics, Retrieved, 11/29/2018 https://www.transtats.bts.gov/airports.asp?pn=1&Airport=TRI&Airport_Name=Bristol/Johnson</ref>\n\n===Highways===\n[[U.S. Route 11]], [[U.S. Route 19]] and [[U.S. Route 421]] run through the city.<ref>City location https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?pagename=Bristol,_Virginia&params=36_36_N_82_11_W_region:US-VA_type:city</ref>\n\nIn the vicinity, to the northwest, is [[Interstate 81]], which takes travelers northward to [[Roanoke, Virginia|Roanoke]], about {{convert|150|mi|km}} away and southward to [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] about {{convert|113|mi|km}} to the south. [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] is {{convert|293|mi|km}} southwest.\n\n===Rail===\nUntil 1970 the [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern Railway]] ran a couple of trains through the city, making stops at [[Bristol station (Virginia)|Bristol station]]. The last trains being the ''[[Birmingham Special]]'' and the ''[[Pelican (train)|Pelican]].'' Until 1968 the [[Memphis, TN|Memphis]]-bound ''[[Tennessean (train)|Tennessean]]'' made a stop in the city.\n\n==Economy==\n\n===Top employers===\nAccording to Bristol's 2011 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristolva.org/archives/38/BVA_audit_2011.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-12-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731180554/http://www.bristolva.org/archives/38/BVA_audit_2011.pdf |archivedate=2013-07-31 }}</ref> the top employers in the city are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\"\n|-\n! #\n! Employer\n! # of Employees\n|-\n|1\n| City of Bristol\n|676\n|-\n|2\n| Electro-Mechanical Corporation\n|600\n|-\n|3\n| [[OfficeMax]]\n|500\n|-\n|4\n| [[Sprint PCS]]\n|428\n|-\n|5\n| US Solutions\n|367\n|-\n|6\n| Strongwell\n|350\n|-\n|7\n|[[Virginia|Commonwealth of Virginia]]\n|250\n|-\n|8\n| [[Shearer's Foods]]\n|225\n|-\n|9\n| [[Ball Corporation|Ball]]\n|218\n|-\n|10\n| [[Aerus]]\n|201\n|-\n|11\n| [[United Parcel Service]]\n|193\n|}\n\n==Education==\nIn 2007 and 2008, Bristol was named one of the Best 100 Communities for Music Education<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amc-music.com/news/articles/survey/final2007.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-04-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516005916/http://www.amc-music.com/news/articles/survey/final2007.htm |archivedate=2008-05-16 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.namm.org/press-room/news/news-releases/2008April29a |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-05-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502164322/http://www.namm.org/press-room/news/news-releases/2008April29a |archivedate=2008-05-02 }}</ref>\n\nThe city school division, [[Bristol Virginia Public Schools]], operates [[Virginia High School (Virginia)|Virginia High School]] and [[Virginia Middle School]], together with four elementary schools: Highland View, Stonewall Jackson, [[Van Pelt Elementary School|Van Pelt]], and Washington Lee.  Three private schools \u2014 St. Anne Catholic, [[Sullins Academy]], and Morrison \u2014 are operated within the city.  Bristol was formerly home to two post-secondary institutions, [[Sullins College]] and [[Virginia Intermont College]], but these colleges closed in 1978 and 2014 respectively.\n\n==Culture==\n=== \"Birthplace of Country Music\" ===\nBristol was recognized as the \"Birthplace of Country Music\", according to a resolution passed by the US Congress in 1998;<ref>{{cite book|last1=Phillips|first1=V.N. (Bud)|title=A good place to live : Bristol, Tennessee/Virginia|date=2006|publisher=Overmountain Press|location=Johnson City, Tenn.|isbn=9781570723148|page=211|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bi528RDRdBIC&pg=PA211#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> residents of the city had contributed to early [[country music]] recordings and influence, and the [[Birthplace of Country Music Museum]] is located in Bristol.\n\nIn 1927 record producer [[Ralph Peer]] of Victor Records began recording local musicians in Bristol to attempt to capture the local sound of traditional \"folk\" music of the region. One of these local sounds was created by the [[Carter Family]]. The Carter Family got their start on July 31, 1927, when A.P. Carter and his family journeyed from [[Maces Spring, Virginia]], to Bristol, Tennessee, to audition for Peer who was seeking new talent for the relatively embryonic recording industry. They received $50 for each song they recorded.\n\nSince 1994, the Birthplace of Country Music Alliance has promoted the city as a destination to learn about the history of the region and its role in the creation of an entire music genre. The Alliance is organizing the building of a new Cultural Heritage Center to help educate the public about the history of country music in the region.<ref>{{cite web|title=Birthplace of Country Music|url=http://www.birthplaceofcountrymusic.org/|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Professional sports ===\nBristol hosts the [[Bristol Pirates]] baseball team of the [[Appalachian League]].\n\nFormer [[NASCAR]] driver [[Kelly Denton]] is from the city.\n\nOn the Tennessee side, Bristol is home to [[Bristol Motor Speedway]], the \"world's fastest half mile\", which hosts two races per year on the NASCAR [[Sprint Cup Series|Sprint Cup]] circuit, two races per year on the NASCAR [[Xfinity Series]] circuit, one race per year on the [[Camping World Truck Series]] circuit, and various other racing events. The complex includes the [[Bristol Dragway]], nicknamed \"Thunder Valley\", referencing the hills that echo the engine noise back toward the crowd.\n\n=== Media ===\nTelevision:\n* [[WCYB-TV]] in Bristol, VA (NBC Channel 5)\n* [[WEMT]]-TV in Bristol, VA (Fox Channel 39)\n* [[WJHL]]-TV in Johnson City, TN (CBS Channel 11; ABC on [[WJHL-DT2|DT2]])\n\nNewspaper:\n* ''[[Bristol Herald Courier]]''\n\nRadio:\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[WEXX|WEXX 99.3 FM]]\n* [[WAEZ|WAEZ 94.9 FM]]\n* [[WXBQ-FM|WXBQ 96.9 FM]]\n* [[WKJV-LP|WKJV 106.5 FM]]\n* [[WZAP|WZAP 690 AM]]\n* [[WWTB|WWTB 980 AM]]\n* [[WOPI (AM)|WOPI 1490 AM]]\n* [[WIGN 1550 AM]]\n* [[WBCM-LP|WBCM-LP 100.1]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Bristol, Virginia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Bristol (Tennessee)}}\n{{Commons category|Bristol, Virginia}}\n* [http://www.bristolva.org/ City of Bristol official website]\n* [http://www.bvps.org/ Bristol Virginia Public Schools]\n* [http://bristolymca.net YMCA of Bristol]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080921223920/http://www.accessbristolva.com/OED_home.html Bristol Virginia Office of Economic Development]\n* [http://www.believeinbristol.org/ Believe in Bristol]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/Ilovestatestreet/ I Love State Street]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/fuzzphotoz/collections/72157616149641002/ Bristol Pictures]\n* [http://www.sullinsacademy.org/ Sullins Academy]\n* [http://www.stanneschoolbristol.org/ St. Anne School]\n* [http://www.morrisonschool.org/ Morrison School]\n{{Coord|display=title|36.6111|-82.1762}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Bristol, Virginia\n|North     = [[Washington County, Virginia|Washington County]]\n|Northeast =\n|East      = [[Washington County, Virginia|Washington County]]\n|Southeast =\n|South     = [[Sullivan County, Tennessee]]\n|Southwest =\n|West      = [[Washington County, Virginia|Washington County]]\n|Northwest =\n}}\n{{Virginia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bristol, Virginia| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Virginia|Bristol, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Divided cities|Bristol, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Twin cities|Bristol, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Kingsport\u2013Bristol metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Southwest Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "No1lakersfan", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated population with 2019 estimates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bristol,_Virginia"}
{"title_page": "Temple Israel (Tulsa, Oklahoma)", "text_new": "{{For|other synagogues named \"Temple Israel\"|Temple Israel (disambiguation){{!}}Temple Israel}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| building_name         =Temple Israel\n| image                 =TI Rockford Tulsa.jpg\n| image_upright = \n| caption               =\n| map_type              =\n| map_size              =\n| map_caption           =\n| location              =2004 East 22nd Place,<br/>[[Tulsa, Oklahoma]],<br/>{{flag|United States}}\n| geo                   = {{coord|36.130579|-95.962776|display=inline,title}}\n| religious_affiliation =[[Reform Judaism]]\n| rite                  =\n| region                =\n| province              =\n| territory             =\n| prefecture            =\n| sector                =\n| district              =\n| cercle                =\n| municipality          =\n| consecration_year     =\n| status                =\n| functional_status     =Active\n| heritage_designation  =\n| leadership            =Rabbi:&nbsp;Michael&nbsp;Weinstein<br/>Cantor:&nbsp;Laurie&nbsp;Weinstein<ref name=Professional/>\n| website               ={{url|templetulsa.com}}\n| architecture          =yes\n| architect             =[[Percival Goodman]]\n| architecture_type     =\n| architecture_style    =\n| general_contractor    =\n| facade_direction      =\n| groundbreaking        =\n| year_completed        =1955\n| construction_cost     =\n| specifications        =\n| capacity              =\n| length                =\n| width                 =\n| width_nave            =\n| height_max            =\n| dome_quantity         =\n| dome_height_outer     =\n| dome_height_inner     =\n| dome_dia_outer        =\n| dome_dia_inner        =\n| minaret_quantity      =\n| minaret_height        =\n| spire_quantity        =\n| spire_height          =\n| materials             =\n| nrhp                  =\n| added                 =\n| refnum                =\n| designated            =\n}}\n'''Temple Israel''' is a [[Reform Judaism|Reform Jewish]] congregation located at 2004 East 22nd Place in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]].<ref name=Homepage>[[#refHomepage|Temple Israel website]].</ref> Founded in 1914, the [[synagogue]] affiliated with the [[Union for Reform Judaism]] in 1915, and constructed its first building on the corner of 14th and Cheyenne Streets in 1919. Early [[rabbi]]s included Jacob Menkes, Charles Latz, Samuel Kaplan, Jacob Krohngold, and Benjamin Kelsen.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297/><ref name=Pilchik1943p322/>\n\nIn 1932, Temple Israel constructed a new building on South Cheyenne. Rabbis there included Hyman Iola, Abraham Shusterman, Randall Falk, and Morton C. Fierman. In 1955 the congregation moved to its current home, a building on East 22nd Place designed by [[Percival Goodman]]. Rabbis serving in this building have included Norbert Rosenthal (1951\u20131976), Charles Sherman (1976\u20132013),<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297/> and Karen and Micah Citrin (2013\u20132016),<ref name=Sherman2013/> Jim Simon (2016-2018),<ref name=Sherman2016/> and Michael Weinstein (2018\u2013present).<ref name=Professional/>\n\nMembership rose from 54 families in 1919<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> to 170 in 1943<ref name=Pilchik1943p322/> and peaked at 585 families in 1985,<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> but fell to 425 by 2011,<ref name=Homepage/> and 375 by 2019.<ref name=Welcome/> Temple Israel is Tulsa's oldest synagogue, and only Reform synagogue.<ref name=Sherman2014/>\n\n==Early history, South Cheyenne building==\nTemple Israel was founded in December 1914, and joined the Union of American Hebrew Congregations (now [[Union for Reform Judaism]]) in 1915.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297>[[#refOlitzkyRaphael1996|Olitzky & Raphael (1996)]], p.&nbsp; 297.</ref><ref name=Pilchik1943p322>[[#refPilchik1943|Pilchik (1943)]], p.&nbsp; 322.</ref> That year the congregation held its first services, for [[Rosh Hashanah]].<ref name=ISJLTulsa>[[#refISJLTulsa|Tulsa, Oklahoma, Institute of Southern Jewish Life (2017)]].</ref> Its first religious leader was Abraham Feldman, who, at the time, was studying at the Reform [[Hebrew Union College]] in Cincinnati. He served until 1915. In 1917, the members hired Jacob B. Menkes as their first [[rabbi]].<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297/> A 1910 graduate of the [[Jewish Theological Seminary of America]],<ref name=deHaas1934p251>[[#refdeHaas1934|de Haas (1934)]], p.&nbsp;251.</ref> he served until 1919;<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297/> at the time, the congregation had just 54 members.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/>\n\nThat year the congregation occupied its first permanent building (until then services had been held in a series of temporary premises),<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297/> at a cost of $75,000 (today ${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|75000|1919|r=-4}}}}).<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> Located at 1306 South Cheyenne (at 14th Street),<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297/> it was, according to some sources, the oldest synagogue building in Oklahoma.<ref>See [[#refLoren2009|Loren (2009)]]. Note, however, that other claimants for \"oldest synagogue building in Oklahoma\" include [http://www.americanjewisharchives.org/aja/FindingAids/TempleEmeth.html Temple Emeth] in [[Ardmore, Oklahoma|Ardmore]] (1912), [http://www.pluralism.org/research/profiles/display.php?profile=75020 B'nai Emunah] in Tulsa (1916), and [http://www.emanuelokc.org/history.htm Emanuel Synagogue] in [[Oklahoma City]] (1917).</ref> It was eventually abandoned and fell into disuse, occupied only by the homeless seeking shelter, and was severely damaged by a fire on January 27, 2009, in which the roof and floors collapsed.<ref name=Loren2009>[[#refLoren2009|Loren (2009)]].</ref><ref name=Stanley2009>[[#refStanley2009|Stanley (2009)]].</ref> In 2009, real estate developer Kevin Stephens stated that he planned to move forward with plans to save its facade and develop the building into a center for sustainability, community, and non-profit space.<ref name=Nicks2009>[[#refNicks2009|Nicks (2009)]], p.&nbsp; 14.</ref><ref name=Easterling2009>[[#refEasterling2009|Easterling (2009)]].</ref>\n\nCharles B. Latz, a 1914 graduate of Hebrew Union College,<ref name=deHaas1934p204>[[#refdeHaas1934|de Haas (1934)]], p.&nbsp;204.</ref> succeeded Menkes as rabbi in 1919.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298>[[#refOlitzkyRaphael1996|Olitzky & Raphael (1996)]], p.&nbsp; 298.</ref> That same year a synagogue sisterhood was formed, followed the next year by a brotherhood.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> During the early 1920s the Tulsa [[All Souls Unitarian Church (Tulsa, Oklahoma)|All Souls Unitarian Church]] (founded 1921) met for a time in Temple Israel's building.<ref name=JoyceHarris2007p213>[[#refJoyceHarris2007|Joyce & Harris (2007)]], p.&nbsp; 213.</ref> At that time, some members proposed hiring the rabbi of Tulsa's [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] synagogue B'nai Emunah and merging with that congregation; the members were even willing to use the Orthodox ''[[siddur]]'' and wear ''[[kippah]]s''; the merger did not go through.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/>\n\nLatz served until 1924.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> He was followed by Samuel S. Kaplan, a 1920 graduate of Hebrew Union College,<ref name=deHaas1934p204/> who served from 1924 to 1927, then Jacob P. Krohngold, who joined in 1927.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> 1929 saw three rabbis at Temple Israel; Krohngold, who left that year, Benjamin Kelsen, who came and left that year, and Hyman Iola,<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> a 1921 graduate of Hebrew Union College.<ref name=deHaas1934p204/>\n\n==South Rockford building==\nDuring Iola's tenure, in 1932, Temple Israel moved to another building, at 1602 South Rockford (at 16th Street),in what is now the [[Swan Lake (Tulsa)|Swan Lake]] [[Historic district (United States)|historic district]].<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/><ref name=TulsaPreservation>[[#refTulsaPreservation|Representative Sample of Properties, Swan Lake Historic District, Tulsa Preservation Commission website]].</ref> That same year the congregation formed a choir. Iola was succeeded in 1935 by Abraham Shusterman.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> A 1931 graduate of Hebrew Union College,<ref name=deHaas1934p204/> he served until 1941,<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> moving to Baltimore, Maryland's [[Har Sinai Congregation]].<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p162>[[#refOlitzkyRaphael1996|Olitzky & Raphael (1996)]], p.&nbsp; 162.</ref> More traditional than his predecessors, Shusterman wore a [[clerical clothing|robe]] and ''[[tallit]]'' (not a business suit) during services, introduced [[bar mitzvah]] ceremonies to Temple Israel, added [[Torah]] readings to the Friday night services, and [[Hebrew language]] instruction in Temple Israel's religious school.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/><ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> Membership grew to 200 families by 1935.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/>\n\nShusterman was replaced in 1941 by Ely E. Pilchik.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> Pilchik had been born in [[Baranovichi|Baranowicz, Poland]], and had immigrated to the United States in 1920. He was a graduate of Hebrew Union College, but \"was more traditional than the typical Reform rabbi\".<ref name=Helmreich1999p257>[[#refHelmreich1999|Helmreich (1999)]], p.&nbsp; 257.</ref> By 1943, the congregation had fallen to around 170 member families,<ref name=Pilchik1943p322/> but by 1945 it was up to 215 families.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> Pilchik served until 1947, moving to Newark, New Jersey's Temple B'nai Jeshurun.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p215>[[#refOlitzkyRaphael1996|Olitzky & Raphael (1996)]], p.&nbsp; 215.</ref>\n\nRandall M. Falk also joined as rabbi in 1945. His tenure was only one year, until 1946, and he focused on Temple Israel's religious school. In 1947 Morton C. Fierman joined as rabbi, succeeding Pilchik, and served until 1951.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/>\n\nFierman was succeed in 1951 by Norbert L. Rosenthal, who concentrated on \"a variety of holiday celebrations and educational programs\".<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> Rosenthal had previously served as rabbi of Old York Road Temple in [[Willow Grove, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=Schwartz>[[#refSchwartz|Schwartz]].</ref> In 1972, he allowed [[Oral Roberts]] to address the congregation at the bar mitzvah of a member.<ref name=PatelHartman2009>[[#refPatelHartman2009|Patel & Hartman (2009)]].</ref> Rosenthal served until 1976,<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> becoming rabbi emeritus until 1990.<ref name=Sherman2014>[[#refSherman2014|Sherman (2014)]].</ref> In 1981, he assisted in the establishing of [[Temple Shalom of Northwest Arkansas]], and served thereafter as its first rabbi, visiting every other week to conduct Friday services.<ref name=GrayLeMaster1994p370>[[#refGrayLeMaster1994|Gray LeMaster (1994)]], p.&nbsp; 370.</ref>\n\nDuring Rosenthal's tenure membership continued to grow, and the South Rockford building became too small to accommodate High Holiday services, which were held instead at the Tulsa University Student Union building.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> In 1955, the congregation moved to its present home at 2004 East 22nd Place,<ref name=Homepage/><ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> just south of the [[Utica Square]] Shopping Center.<ref name=About>[[#refAbout|About Us, Temple Israel website]].</ref> The South Rockford building was sold to Christ the King Catholic Church, which remodeled it so that it could be used as a [[fellowship hall]]. In 1975 it was renamed Fletcher Hall, after the former [[parish]] priest, and in 1991 it was removed to make way for a playground for students at [[Marquette Catholic School (Tulsa, Oklahoma)|Marquette Catholic School]].<ref name=TulsaPreservation/>\n\n==East 22nd Place building==\nDesigned by prolific synagogue architect [[Percival Goodman]], the East 22nd Place synagogue's front is dominated by massive twin pillars displaying the [[Ten Commandments]],<ref name=Wall1979>[[#refWall1979|Wall (1979)]], p.&nbsp; 8.</ref> which represent the biblical [[Pillar of Fire (theophany)|Pillar of Fire]] and the [[Pillar of Cloud (theophany)|Pillar of Cloud]].<ref name=Kampfpp189-190>[[#refKampf1966|Kampf (1966)]], pp.&nbsp; 189\u2013190.</ref> Goodman hired the sculptor [[Seymour Lipton]] to produce three works of ceremonial art for the sanctuary's ''[[Bema#Judaism|bimah]]'', \"a ''[[ner tamid]]'', a monumental seven-branch ''[[Menorah (Temple)|menorah]]'', and an abstracted, vine motif that is placed along the top of the [[Torah Ark]].\"<ref name=Kampfpp189-190/><ref name=Gilbert2004>[[#refGilbert2004|Gilbert (2004)]].</ref> The shape of the ''ner tamid'' \"represents two sets of angels' wings that were set over the [[Ark of the Covenant|Ark]] in the ancient [[Solomon's Temple|Temple of Solomon]].\" The vine decoration contains [[pomegranates]], \"an ancient symbol of fruitfulness.\" The ''menorah'', which is lit Fridays and holidays, \"is symbolic of the [[Tree of Life]]\".<ref name=Sanctuary>[[#refSanctuary|Sanctuary, Tour, Temple Israel website]].</ref> By 1962 membership had grown to 385 families.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/>\n\nCharles P. Sherman joined as rabbi in 1976 and retired in 2013. Originally from Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, he graduated from the [[University of Pittsburgh]] and was ordained at  Hebrew Union College in 1969.<ref name=TulsaHistorical>[[#refTulsaHistorical|2005 Hall of Fame Inductees, Tulsa Historical Society]].</ref>  At Temple Israel, he focused on education, and created programs for mixed Jewish/non-Jewish couples and [[Conversion to Judaism|converts to Judaism]]. He was a strong supporter of the Oklahoma Chapter of the Religious Coalition for Abortion Rights, and garnered support for it from the Southwest Council of the Union of American Hebrew Congregations (now Union for Reform Judaism).<ref name=Joyce1998p309>[[#refJoyce1998|Joyce (1998)]], p.&nbsp; 309.</ref> He also \"advocated social justice and religious action, as well as fuller participation in the Reform movement and community at large.\"<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> While rabbi at Temple Israel, he also taught at the [[University of Tulsa]] and [[Phillips Theological Seminary]], and served as president of the Southwest Association of Reform Rabbis, the Tulsa Ministerial Alliance, the Tulsa Police and Fire Chaplaincy Corps, the [[National Conference for Community and Justice]] (Tulsa Region) and the Tulsa Metropolitan Ministry.<ref name=TulsaHistorical/> In 1979, he presided over the bar mitzvah at Temple Israel of future NFL [[American football|football]] player and [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] [[Bill Goldberg]].<ref name=Farhi1999>[[#refFarhi1999|Farhi (1999)]].</ref> That year membership was 525 families.<ref name=Wall1979/>\n\nIn 1984 the synagogue building flooded, and as part of the repairs, the congregation added a preschool.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> The following year membership peaked at 558 families,<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> but by 1995 that had fallen to under 500.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> Sherman was inducted into the Tulsa Historical Society Hall of Fame in 2005,<ref name=TulsaHistorical/> and in 2010 he was awarded the Russell Bennett Spiritual Inclusion Award by the Oklahomans for Equality.<ref name=OklahomansForEquality>[[#refOklahomansForEquality|Oklahomans for Equality Award Recipients 2010, Oklahomans for Equality website]].</ref> Sherman retired in 2013, becoming rabbi emeritus.<ref name=Professional>[[#refProfessional|Professional Staff, Temple Israel website]].</ref>\n\nTo succeed Sherman, Temple Israel selected a married couple, Micah and Karen Citrin, who had previously worked together as rabbis at Peninsula Temple Beth El in San Mateo, California.  The Citrins met when both of them were studying for the rabbinate at Hebrew Union College in Los Angeles.  Micah's father was the rabbi at New Mexico's oldest Jewish congregation, [[Congregation Albert]] in Albuquerque.<ref name=Sherman2013>[[#refSherman2013|Sherman (2013)]].</ref> The Citrins moved to Temple Beth David in Westwood, Massachusetts in 2016, and were succeeded by Jim Simon as interim rabbi.<ref name=Sherman2016>[[#refSherman2016|Sherman (2016)]].</ref>\n\nMichael Weinstein became Temple Israel's rabbi in 2018. A graduate of [[University of Cincinnati]] and [[Xavier University]] (where he completed a Master's degree in [[Christian theology]]), he received his rabbinic ordination from Hebrew Union College in 2010. His wife Laurie Weinstein was appointed as the synagogue's cantor.<ref name=Professional/>\n\nTemple Israel's membership has continued to fall, to 425 families in 2011,<ref name=Homepage/> and 375 by 2019.<ref name=Welcome>[[#refWelcome|About, Temple Israel website]].</ref> Temple Israel is Tulsa's oldest synagogue, and only Reform synagogue.<ref name=Sherman2014/>\n\n==Notable members==\n*[[Bill Goldberg]], NFL football player and undefeated wrestler<ref name=Farhi1999/>\n*[[Benedict I. Lubell]], oil industry executive<ref>{{cite news|title=Funeral Services Set for Tulsa Arts Patron Benedict I. Lubell   |newspaper=[[Tulsa World]]|date=December 14, 1996  |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/archives/funeral-services-set-for-tulsa-arts-patron-benedict-i-lubell/article_4fafa1e2-d1ee-5ea8-8d41-d1a07c9a628e.html  }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|33em}}\n*<span id=\"refdeHaas1934\" class=\"citation\">[[Jacob de Haas|de Haas, Jacob]] (ed.) ''The Encyclopedia of Jewish Knowledge'', Behrman, 1934.</span>\n*<span id=\"refEasterling2009\" class=\"citation\">Easterling, Mike. [http://www.urbantulsa.com/gyrobase/Content?oid=oid%3A28748 \"Recycle That Building: Entrepreneur donates historic temple to be re-used as center for conservation and sustainability\"], ''Urban Tulsa Weekly'', December 9, 2009.</span>\n*<span id=\"refFarhi1999\" class=\"citation\">Farhi, Paul. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/feed/a35654-1999dec9.htm \"Goldberg: A David in Goliath's Shoes\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', December 9, 1999.</span>\n*<span id=\"refGilbert2004\" class=\"citation\">Gilbert, Barbara. [http://www.bookrags.com/tandf/lipton-seymour-tf/ \"Lipton, Seymour (1905\u201386)\"], ''Encyclopedia of Modern Jewish Culture, Volume 1'', [[Taylor & Francis]], 2004. {{ISBN|0-203-49435-0}}</span>\n*<span id=\"refGrayLeMaster1994\" class=\"citation\">Gray LeMaster, Caroline. ''A Corner of the Tapestry: A History of the Jewish Experience in Arkansas, 1820s\u20131990s'', [[University of Arkansas Press]], 1994. {{ISBN|978-1-55728-304-7}}</span>\n*<span id=\"refHelmreich1999\" class=\"citation\">Helmreich, William B. ''The Enduring Community: the Jews of Newark and MetroWest'', Transaction Publishers, 1999. {{ISBN|978-1-56000-392-2}}</span>\n*<span id=\"refISJLTulsa\" class=\"citation\">[https://www.isjl.org/oklahoma-tulsa-encyclopedia.html Tulsa, Oklahoma], [[Goldring / Woldenberg Institute of Southern Jewish Life]], History Department, Encyclopedia, Tennessee, Memphis, 2017. Accessed {{Nowrap|March 28}}, 2019.</span>\n*<span id=\"refJoyce1998\" class=\"citation\">Joyce, Davis D. ''Oklahoma I Had Never Seen Before: Alternative Views of Oklahoma History'', [[University of Oklahoma Press]], 1998. {{ISBN|978-0-8061-2945-7}}</span>\n*<span id=\"refJoyceHarris2007\" class=\"citation\">Joyce, Davis D.; Harris, Fred R. ''Alternative Oklahoma: Contrarian Views of the Sooner State'', [[University of Oklahoma Press]], 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-8061-3819-0}}</span>\n*<span id=\"refKampf1966\" class=\"citation\">Kampf, Avram. ''Contemporary Synagogue Art: developments in the United States, 1945-1965'', [[Union of American Hebrew Congregations]], 1966, {{OCLC|338352}}, pp.&nbsp; 118\u2013120, 188\u2013192.</span>\n*<span id=\"refLoren2009\" class=\"citation\">Loren, Jennifer. [http://www.newson6.com/Global/story.asp?s=9738621 \"Tulsa Fire Crews Battle Synagogue Fire\"]. ''The News On 6'', January 27, 2009.</span>\n*<span id=\"refNicks2009\" class=\"citation\">Nicks, Denver. [http://www.tulsapeople-digital.com/tulsapeople/200904/?pg=14 \"Urban Cowboy: Developer Kevin Stephens aims to develop mixed-use, urban environments that will bring people back downtown\"], ''Tulsa People'', April 2009, p.&nbsp; 14.</span>\n*<span id=\"refOklahomansForEquality\" class=\"citation\">[http://www.okeq.org/2010/02/27/oklahomans-for-equality-award-recipients-2010/ \"Oklahomans for Equality Award Recipients 2010\"], Oklahomans for Equality website. Accessed June 24, 2010.</span>\n*<span id=\"refOlitzkyRaphael1996\" class=\"citation\">[[Kerry Olitzky|Olitzky, Kerry M.]]; Raphael, Marc Lee. ''The American Synagogue: A Historical Dictionary and Sourcebook'', [[Greenwood Publishing Group|Greenwood Press]], 1996. {{ISBN|978-0-313-28856-2}}</span>\n*<span id=\"refPatelHartman2009\" class=\"citation\">[[Eboo Patel|Patel, Eboo]]; Hartman, Becca. [http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/eboo_patel/2009/12/heres_to_you_mrs_moskowitz_ora.html \"Oral Roberts at a bar mitzvah\"], On Faith, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' online, December 16, 2009.</span>\n*<span id=\"refPilchik1943\" class=\"citation\">Pilchik, Ely E., \"Tulsa\", in [[Isaac Landman|Landman, Isaac]] (ed.). ''The Universal Jewish Encyclopedia'', Volume 10, Universal Jewish Encyclopedia Co. Inc., 1943.</span>\n*<span id=\"refSchwartz\" class=\"citation\">Schwartz, Herbert. [http://www.oyrtbetham.org/BEGINNINGS.html \"The Beginnings of Old York Road Temple - Beth Am\"], Old York Road Temple - Beth Am website. Accessed June 24, 2010.</span>\n*<span id=\"refSherman2013\" class=\"citation\">Sherman, Bill. [http://www.tulsaworld.com/article.aspx/Married_couple_to_serve_as_co_rabbis_at_Tulsas_Temple/20130216_18_a15_cutlin553766 \"Married couple to serve as co-rabbis at Tulsa's Temple Israel\"]. ''[[Tulsa World]]'', February 16, 2013.</span>\n*<span id=\"refSherman2014\" class=\"citation\">Sherman, Bill. [https://www.tulsaworld.com/lifestyles/temple-israel-begins-celebration-of-th-anniversary-on-friday/article_c92d9081-b93d-5f83-9dc9-e7e4a5f26942.html \"Temple Israel begins celebration of 100th anniversary on Friday\"]. ''[[Tulsa World]]'', November 14, 2014.</span>\n*<span id=\"refSherman2016\" class=\"citation\">Sherman, Bill. [https://www.tulsaworld.com/lifestyles/interim-rabbi-at-temple-israel-to-ease-transition/article_96aa388f-e664-5b8c-b597-2c96a6fd0978.html \"Interim rabbi at Temple Israel to ease transition\"]. ''[[Tulsa World]]'', July 9, 2016.</span>\n*<span id=\"refStanley2009\" class=\"citation\">Stanley, Tim. [http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/article.aspx?subjectid=11&articleid=20090128_11_A9_Firefi808930&allcom=1 \"Historic synagogue burns\"] ''[[Tulsa World]]'', January 28, 2009.</span>\n*<span id=\"refHomepage\" class=\"citation\">[http://www.templetulsa.com/index.php Temple Israel website]. Accessed June 23, 2010.</span>\n**<span id=\"refWelcome\" class=\"citation\">[http://www.templetulsa.com/#welcome1 \"About\"], Temple Israel website. Accessed March 28, 2019.</span>\n**<span id=\"refAbout\" class=\"citation\">[http://www.templetulsa.com/pages/about-us.php \"About Us\"], Temple Israel website. Accessed June 24, 2010.</span>\n**<span id=\"refProfessional\" class=\"citation\">[http://www.templetulsa.com/professional-staff \"Professional Staff\"], Temple Israel website. Accessed March 28, 2019.</span>\n**<span id=\"refSanctuary\" class=\"citation\">[http://www.templetulsa.com/pages/tour/4.php \"Sanctuary\"], Tour, Temple Israel website. Accessed June 24, 2010.</span>\n**<span id=\"refStaff\" class=\"citation\">[http://www.templetulsa.com/pages/staff/professional-staff.php \"Professional Staff\"], Temple Israel website. Accessed June 24, 2010.</span>\n*<span id=\"refTulsaHistorical\" class=\"citation\">[http://www.tulsahistory.org/hof/sherman.htm \"Rabbi Charles P. Sherman\"], 2005 Hall of Fame Inductees, Tulsa Historical Society website. Accessed June 24, 2010.</span>\n*<span id=\"refTulsaPreservation\" class=\"citation\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20150330231133/http://www.tulsapreservationcommission.org/nationalregister/districts/swanlake/properties/ \"Representative Sample of Properties, Swan Lake Historic District\"], Tulsa Preservation Commission website. Accessed June 24, 2010.</span>\n*<span id=\"refWall1979\" class=\"citation\">{{cite journal|last=Wall |first=Judith |title=Holidays Mean Holy Days for Most Oklahomans |url= http://digital.library.okstate.edu/oktoday/1980s/1980/oktdv30n1.pdf |journal=Oklahoma Today |volume=30 |number=1 |date=Winter 1979 |pages=4\u201311}}.</span>\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n*Zarrow, Alison. ''Abandoned Tulsa'', Furnace Press, 2005, {{ISBN|978-0-9772742-2-2}}, pp.&nbsp; 53-61.\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Israel (Tulsa, Oklahoma)}}\n[[Category:1914 establishments in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Percival Goodman synagogues]]\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Reform synagogues in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Jewish organizations established in 1914]]\n[[Category:Synagogues completed in 1955]]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.voicesofoklahoma.com/interview/sherman-rabbi-charles/ Voices of Oklahoma interview.] Two first person interviews conducted on June 10, 2013 and February 19, 2020, with Rabbi Charles Sherman.\n", "text_old": "{{For|other synagogues named \"Temple Israel\"|Temple Israel (disambiguation){{!}}Temple Israel}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| building_name         =Temple Israel\n| image                 =TI Rockford Tulsa.jpg\n| image_upright = \n| caption               =\n| map_type              =\n| map_size              =\n| map_caption           =\n| location              =2004 East 22nd Place,<br/>[[Tulsa, Oklahoma]],<br/>{{flag|United States}}\n| geo                   = {{coord|36.130579|-95.962776|display=inline,title}}\n| religious_affiliation =[[Reform Judaism]]\n| rite                  =\n| region                =\n| province              =\n| territory             =\n| prefecture            =\n| sector                =\n| district              =\n| cercle                =\n| municipality          =\n| consecration_year     =\n| status                =\n| functional_status     =Active\n| heritage_designation  =\n| leadership            =Rabbi:&nbsp;Michael&nbsp;Weinstein<br/>Cantor:&nbsp;Laurie&nbsp;Weinstein<ref name=Professional/>\n| website               ={{url|templetulsa.com}}\n| architecture          =yes\n| architect             =[[Percival Goodman]]\n| architecture_type     =\n| architecture_style    =\n| general_contractor    =\n| facade_direction      =\n| groundbreaking        =\n| year_completed        =1955\n| construction_cost     =\n| specifications        =\n| capacity              =\n| length                =\n| width                 =\n| width_nave            =\n| height_max            =\n| dome_quantity         =\n| dome_height_outer     =\n| dome_height_inner     =\n| dome_dia_outer        =\n| dome_dia_inner        =\n| minaret_quantity      =\n| minaret_height        =\n| spire_quantity        =\n| spire_height          =\n| materials             =\n| nrhp                  =\n| added                 =\n| refnum                =\n| designated            =\n}}\n'''Temple Israel''' is a [[Reform Judaism|Reform Jewish]] congregation located at 2004 East 22nd Place in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]].<ref name=Homepage>[[#refHomepage|Temple Israel website]].</ref> Founded in 1914, the [[synagogue]] affiliated with the [[Union for Reform Judaism]] in 1915, and constructed its first building on the corner of 14th and Cheyenne Streets in 1919. Early [[rabbi]]s included Jacob Menkes, Charles Latz, Samuel Kaplan, Jacob Krohngold, and Benjamin Kelsen.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297/><ref name=Pilchik1943p322/>\n\nIn 1932, Temple Israel constructed a new building on South Cheyenne. Rabbis there included Hyman Iola, Abraham Shusterman, Randall Falk, and Morton C. Fierman. In 1955 the congregation moved to its current home, a building on East 22nd Place designed by [[Percival Goodman]]. Rabbis serving in this building have included Norbert Rosenthal (1951\u20131976), Charles Sherman (1976\u20132013),<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297/> and Karen and Micah Citrin (2013\u20132016),<ref name=Sherman2013/> Jim Simon (2016-2018),<ref name=Sherman2016/> and Michael Weinstein (2018\u2013present).<ref name=Professional/>\n\nMembership rose from 54 families in 1919<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> to 170 in 1943<ref name=Pilchik1943p322/> and peaked at 585 families in 1985,<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> but fell to 425 by 2011,<ref name=Homepage/> and 375 by 2019.<ref name=Welcome/> Temple Israel is Tulsa's oldest synagogue, and only Reform synagogue.<ref name=Sherman2014/>\n\n==Early history, South Cheyenne building==\nTemple Israel was founded in December 1914, and joined the Union of American Hebrew Congregations (now [[Union for Reform Judaism]]) in 1915.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297>[[#refOlitzkyRaphael1996|Olitzky & Raphael (1996)]], p.&nbsp; 297.</ref><ref name=Pilchik1943p322>[[#refPilchik1943|Pilchik (1943)]], p.&nbsp; 322.</ref> That year the congregation held its first services, for [[Rosh Hashanah]].<ref name=ISJLTulsa>[[#refISJLTulsa|Tulsa, Oklahoma, Institute of Southern Jewish Life (2017)]].</ref> Its first religious leader was Abraham Feldman, who, at the time, was studying at the Reform [[Hebrew Union College]] in Cincinnati. He served until 1915. In 1917, the members hired Jacob B. Menkes as their first [[rabbi]].<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297/> A 1910 graduate of the [[Jewish Theological Seminary of America]],<ref name=deHaas1934p251>[[#refdeHaas1934|de Haas (1934)]], p.&nbsp;251.</ref> he served until 1919;<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297/> at the time, the congregation had just 54 members.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/>\n\nThat year the congregation occupied its first permanent building (until then services had been held in a series of temporary premises),<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297/> at a cost of $75,000 (today ${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|75000|1919|r=-4}}}}).<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> Located at 1306 South Cheyenne (at 14th Street),<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p297/> it was, according to some sources, the oldest synagogue building in Oklahoma.<ref>See [[#refLoren2009|Loren (2009)]]. Note, however, that other claimants for \"oldest synagogue building in Oklahoma\" include [http://www.americanjewisharchives.org/aja/FindingAids/TempleEmeth.html Temple Emeth] in [[Ardmore, Oklahoma|Ardmore]] (1912), [http://www.pluralism.org/research/profiles/display.php?profile=75020 B'nai Emunah] in Tulsa (1916), and [http://www.emanuelokc.org/history.htm Emanuel Synagogue] in [[Oklahoma City]] (1917).</ref> It was eventually abandoned and fell into disuse, occupied only by the homeless seeking shelter, and was severely damaged by a fire on January 27, 2009, in which the roof and floors collapsed.<ref name=Loren2009>[[#refLoren2009|Loren (2009)]].</ref><ref name=Stanley2009>[[#refStanley2009|Stanley (2009)]].</ref> In 2009, real estate developer Kevin Stephens stated that he planned to move forward with plans to save its facade and develop the building into a center for sustainability, community, and non-profit space.<ref name=Nicks2009>[[#refNicks2009|Nicks (2009)]], p.&nbsp; 14.</ref><ref name=Easterling2009>[[#refEasterling2009|Easterling (2009)]].</ref>\n\nCharles B. Latz, a 1914 graduate of Hebrew Union College,<ref name=deHaas1934p204>[[#refdeHaas1934|de Haas (1934)]], p.&nbsp;204.</ref> succeeded Menkes as rabbi in 1919.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298>[[#refOlitzkyRaphael1996|Olitzky & Raphael (1996)]], p.&nbsp; 298.</ref> That same year a synagogue sisterhood was formed, followed the next year by a brotherhood.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> During the early 1920s the Tulsa [[All Souls Unitarian Church (Tulsa, Oklahoma)|All Souls Unitarian Church]] (founded 1921) met for a time in Temple Israel's building.<ref name=JoyceHarris2007p213>[[#refJoyceHarris2007|Joyce & Harris (2007)]], p.&nbsp; 213.</ref> At that time, some members proposed hiring the rabbi of Tulsa's [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] synagogue B'nai Emunah and merging with that congregation; the members were even willing to use the Orthodox ''[[siddur]]'' and wear ''[[kippah]]s''; the merger did not go through.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/>\n\nLatz served until 1924.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> He was followed by Samuel S. Kaplan, a 1920 graduate of Hebrew Union College,<ref name=deHaas1934p204/> who served from 1924 to 1927, then Jacob P. Krohngold, who joined in 1927.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> 1929 saw three rabbis at Temple Israel; Krohngold, who left that year, Benjamin Kelsen, who came and left that year, and Hyman Iola,<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> a 1921 graduate of Hebrew Union College.<ref name=deHaas1934p204/>\n\n==South Rockford building==\nDuring Iola's tenure, in 1932, Temple Israel moved to another building, at 1602 South Rockford (at 16th Street),in what is now the [[Swan Lake (Tulsa)|Swan Lake]] [[Historic district (United States)|historic district]].<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/><ref name=TulsaPreservation>[[#refTulsaPreservation|Representative Sample of Properties, Swan Lake Historic District, Tulsa Preservation Commission website]].</ref> That same year the congregation formed a choir. Iola was succeeded in 1935 by Abraham Shusterman.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> A 1931 graduate of Hebrew Union College,<ref name=deHaas1934p204/> he served until 1941,<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> moving to Baltimore, Maryland's [[Har Sinai Congregation]].<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p162>[[#refOlitzkyRaphael1996|Olitzky & Raphael (1996)]], p.&nbsp; 162.</ref> More traditional than his predecessors, Shusterman wore a [[clerical clothing|robe]] and ''[[tallit]]'' (not a business suit) during services, introduced [[bar mitzvah]] ceremonies to Temple Israel, added [[Torah]] readings to the Friday night services, and [[Hebrew language]] instruction in Temple Israel's religious school.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/><ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> Membership grew to 200 families by 1935.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/>\n\nShusterman was replaced in 1941 by Ely E. Pilchik.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> Pilchik had been born in [[Baranovichi|Baranowicz, Poland]], and had immigrated to the United States in 1920. He was a graduate of Hebrew Union College, but \"was more traditional than the typical Reform rabbi\".<ref name=Helmreich1999p257>[[#refHelmreich1999|Helmreich (1999)]], p.&nbsp; 257.</ref> By 1943, the congregation had fallen to around 170 member families,<ref name=Pilchik1943p322/> but by 1945 it was up to 215 families.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> Pilchik served until 1947, moving to Newark, New Jersey's Temple B'nai Jeshurun.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p215>[[#refOlitzkyRaphael1996|Olitzky & Raphael (1996)]], p.&nbsp; 215.</ref>\n\nRandall M. Falk also joined as rabbi in 1945. His tenure was only one year, until 1946, and he focused on Temple Israel's religious school. In 1947 Morton C. Fierman joined as rabbi, succeeding Pilchik, and served until 1951.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/>\n\nFierman was succeed in 1951 by Norbert L. Rosenthal, who concentrated on \"a variety of holiday celebrations and educational programs\".<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> Rosenthal had previously served as rabbi of Old York Road Temple in [[Willow Grove, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=Schwartz>[[#refSchwartz|Schwartz]].</ref> In 1972, he allowed [[Oral Roberts]] to address the congregation at the bar mitzvah of a member.<ref name=PatelHartman2009>[[#refPatelHartman2009|Patel & Hartman (2009)]].</ref> Rosenthal served until 1976,<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> becoming rabbi emeritus until 1990.<ref name=Sherman2014>[[#refSherman2014|Sherman (2014)]].</ref> In 1981, he assisted in the establishing of [[Temple Shalom of Northwest Arkansas]], and served thereafter as its first rabbi, visiting every other week to conduct Friday services.<ref name=GrayLeMaster1994p370>[[#refGrayLeMaster1994|Gray LeMaster (1994)]], p.&nbsp; 370.</ref>\n\nDuring Rosenthal's tenure membership continued to grow, and the South Rockford building became too small to accommodate High Holiday services, which were held instead at the Tulsa University Student Union building.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> In 1955, the congregation moved to its present home at 2004 East 22nd Place,<ref name=Homepage/><ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> just south of the [[Utica Square]] Shopping Center.<ref name=About>[[#refAbout|About Us, Temple Israel website]].</ref> The South Rockford building was sold to Christ the King Catholic Church, which remodeled it so that it could be used as a [[fellowship hall]]. In 1975 it was renamed Fletcher Hall, after the former [[parish]] priest, and in 1991 it was removed to make way for a playground for students at [[Marquette Catholic School (Tulsa, Oklahoma)|Marquette Catholic School]].<ref name=TulsaPreservation/>\n\n==East 22nd Place building==\nDesigned by prolific synagogue architect [[Percival Goodman]], the East 22nd Place synagogue's front is dominated by massive twin pillars displaying the [[Ten Commandments]],<ref name=Wall1979>[[#refWall1979|Wall (1979)]], p.&nbsp; 8.</ref> which represent the biblical [[Pillar of Fire (theophany)|Pillar of Fire]] and the [[Pillar of Cloud (theophany)|Pillar of Cloud]].<ref name=Kampfpp189-190>[[#refKampf1966|Kampf (1966)]], pp.&nbsp; 189\u2013190.</ref> Goodman hired the sculptor [[Seymour Lipton]] to produce three works of ceremonial art for the sanctuary's ''[[Bema#Judaism|bimah]]'', \"a ''[[ner tamid]]'', a monumental seven-branch ''[[Menorah (Temple)|menorah]]'', and an abstracted, vine motif that is placed along the top of the [[Torah Ark]].\"<ref name=Kampfpp189-190/><ref name=Gilbert2004>[[#refGilbert2004|Gilbert (2004)]].</ref> The shape of the ''ner tamid'' \"represents two sets of angels' wings that were set over the [[Ark of the Covenant|Ark]] in the ancient [[Solomon's Temple|Temple of Solomon]].\" The vine decoration contains [[pomegranates]], \"an ancient symbol of fruitfulness.\" The ''menorah'', which is lit Fridays and holidays, \"is symbolic of the [[Tree of Life]]\".<ref name=Sanctuary>[[#refSanctuary|Sanctuary, Tour, Temple Israel website]].</ref> By 1962 membership had grown to 385 families.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/>\n\nCharles P. Sherman joined as rabbi in 1976 and retired in 2013. Originally from Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, he graduated from the [[University of Pittsburgh]] and was ordained at  Hebrew Union College in 1969.<ref name=TulsaHistorical>[[#refTulsaHistorical|2005 Hall of Fame Inductees, Tulsa Historical Society]].</ref>  At Temple Israel, he focused on education, and created programs for mixed Jewish/non-Jewish couples and [[Conversion to Judaism|converts to Judaism]]. He was a strong supporter of the Oklahoma Chapter of the Religious Coalition for Abortion Rights, and garnered support for it from the Southwest Council of the Union of American Hebrew Congregations (now Union for Reform Judaism).<ref name=Joyce1998p309>[[#refJoyce1998|Joyce (1998)]], p.&nbsp; 309.</ref> He also \"advocated social justice and religious action, as well as fuller participation in the Reform movement and community at large.\"<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> While rabbi at Temple Israel, he also taught at the [[University of Tulsa]] and [[Phillips Theological Seminary]], and served as president of the Southwest Association of Reform Rabbis, the Tulsa Ministerial Alliance, the Tulsa Police and Fire Chaplaincy Corps, the [[National Conference for Community and Justice]] (Tulsa Region) and the Tulsa Metropolitan Ministry.<ref name=TulsaHistorical/> In 1979, he presided over the bar mitzvah at Temple Israel of future NFL [[American football|football]] player and [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] [[Bill Goldberg]].<ref name=Farhi1999>[[#refFarhi1999|Farhi (1999)]].</ref> That year membership was 525 families.<ref name=Wall1979/>\n\nIn 1984 the synagogue building flooded, and as part of the repairs, the congregation added a preschool.<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> The following year membership peaked at 558 families,<ref name=ISJLTulsa/> but by 1995 that had fallen to under 500.<ref name=OlitzkyRaphael1996p298/> Sherman was inducted into the Tulsa Historical Society Hall of Fame in 2005,<ref name=TulsaHistorical/> and in 2010 he was awarded the Russell Bennett Spiritual Inclusion Award by the Oklahomans for Equality.<ref name=OklahomansForEquality>[[#refOklahomansForEquality|Oklahomans for Equality Award Recipients 2010, Oklahomans for Equality website]].</ref> Sherman retired in 2013, becoming rabbi emeritus.<ref name=Professional>[[#refProfessional|Professional Staff, Temple Israel website]].</ref>\n\nTo succeed Sherman, Temple Israel selected a married couple, Micah and Karen Citrin, who had previously worked together as rabbis at Peninsula Temple Beth El in San Mateo, California.  The Citrins met when both of them were studying for the rabbinate at Hebrew Union College in Los Angeles.  Micah's father was the rabbi at New Mexico's oldest Jewish congregation, [[Congregation Albert]] in Albuquerque.<ref name=Sherman2013>[[#refSherman2013|Sherman (2013)]].</ref> The Citrins moved to Temple Beth David in Westwood, Massachusetts in 2016, and were succeeded by Jim Simon as interim rabbi.<ref name=Sherman2016>[[#refSherman2016|Sherman (2016)]].</ref>\n\nMichael Weinstein became Temple Israel's rabbi in 2018. A graduate of [[University of Cincinnati]] and [[Xavier University]] (where he completed a Master's degree in [[Christian theology]]), he received his rabbinic ordination from Hebrew Union College in 2010. His wife Laurie Weinstein was appointed as the synagogue's cantor.<ref name=Professional/>\n\nTemple Israel's membership has continued to fall, to 425 families in 2011,<ref name=Homepage/> and 375 by 2019.<ref name=Welcome>[[#refWelcome|About, Temple Israel website]].</ref> Temple Israel is Tulsa's oldest synagogue, and only Reform synagogue.<ref name=Sherman2014/>\n\n==Notable members==\n*[[Bill Goldberg]], NFL football player and undefeated wrestler<ref name=Farhi1999/>\n*[[Benedict I. Lubell]], oil industry executive<ref>{{cite news|title=Funeral Services Set for Tulsa Arts Patron Benedict I. Lubell   |newspaper=[[Tulsa World]]|date=December 14, 1996  |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/archives/funeral-services-set-for-tulsa-arts-patron-benedict-i-lubell/article_4fafa1e2-d1ee-5ea8-8d41-d1a07c9a628e.html  }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|33em}}\n*<span id=\"refdeHaas1934\" class=\"citation\">[[Jacob de Haas|de Haas, Jacob]] (ed.) ''The Encyclopedia of Jewish Knowledge'', Behrman, 1934.</span>\n*<span id=\"refEasterling2009\" class=\"citation\">Easterling, Mike. [http://www.urbantulsa.com/gyrobase/Content?oid=oid%3A28748 \"Recycle That Building: Entrepreneur donates historic temple to be re-used as center for conservation and sustainability\"], ''Urban Tulsa Weekly'', December 9, 2009.</span>\n*<span id=\"refFarhi1999\" class=\"citation\">Farhi, Paul. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/feed/a35654-1999dec9.htm \"Goldberg: A David in Goliath's Shoes\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', December 9, 1999.</span>\n*<span id=\"refGilbert2004\" class=\"citation\">Gilbert, Barbara. [http://www.bookrags.com/tandf/lipton-seymour-tf/ \"Lipton, Seymour (1905\u201386)\"], ''Encyclopedia of Modern Jewish Culture, Volume 1'', [[Taylor & Francis]], 2004. {{ISBN|0-203-49435-0}}</span>\n*<span id=\"refGrayLeMaster1994\" class=\"citation\">Gray LeMaster, Caroline. ''A Corner of the Tapestry: A History of the Jewish Experience in Arkansas, 1820s\u20131990s'', [[University of Arkansas Press]], 1994. {{ISBN|978-1-55728-304-7}}</span>\n*<span id=\"refHelmreich1999\" class=\"citation\">Helmreich, William B. ''The Enduring Community: the Jews of Newark and MetroWest'', Transaction Publishers, 1999. {{ISBN|978-1-56000-392-2}}</span>\n*<span id=\"refISJLTulsa\" class=\